<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
BELGIUM; 
</P>
<P>
GUERRILLA IS OFFERED FOR HOSTAGE FAMILY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and Wire reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Belgium said it might free a Palestinian guerrilla from prison if a family of 
four held hostage in Lebanon is released. 
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Mark Eyskens said in Brussels that he had recently met with 
relatives of Emmanuel Houtekins, his wife, Godelieve Kets, and their two 
teen-age children. He said the relatives are "almost desperate." The four were 
seized from a yacht in the Mediterranean in 1987 by a Palestinian group led by 
Abu Nidal. Nasser Said is serving a life sentence for a 1980 grenade attack in 
Antwerp that resulted in the death of a child, but he is eligible for parole 
next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
