WORLD IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
LIBERIA; 
</P>
<P>
TALKS TO RESUME ON ENDING CIVIL WAR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and Wire reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Peace talks in Liberia's six-month civil war are to resume today in Freetown, 
Sierra Leone, a week after breaking up in deadlock. 
</P>
<P>
There is little hope that the talks will succeed unless President Samuel K. Doe 
resigns, rebel observers said. The leader of the government delegation, 
however, said he expects a settlement. "We have come to make peace, and that is 
going to happen," Information Minister J. Emmanuel Bowier said. Meanwhile, the 
government said it captured 79 rebels at the Firestone rubber plantation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
